commentBody:
@Dave S 

That's how I approach a lot of Thursday puzzles. 

In this case, though, I got the revealer and was able to make sense of it before I really had any of the theme answers.

@Eric 
Of course the British spelling of the gerund would properly be impanelling.

That would mess up Ella’s trick!

@Wayne Harrison

I had to look at the answer key to get the IM  prefix.  
No idea about water brands, since I refuse to buy water in little plastic bottles.  Such a waste of plastic!

@Tom 

As long as you follow the directions stated in the revealer (35A), all the theme clues make perfect sense.  You just have to cotton to the trick.


!!!

@JG 

The app wouldn't accept rebuses because this is not a rebus puzzle.  There's a trick, but there's still only one letter to a box.  

How would you have entered multiple letters in one box while maintaining the correct down answers?

@Shrike 

JG said “the app wouldn’t accept rebuses” as if it should have. It wasn’t clear to me that JG understood that there weren’t any rebuses. 

I’m surprised you considered my comment “interrogating”.  I don’t see why.

@Hardroch 

That was indeed very interesting.

I never "got" Sinatra.  His heyday was before my time.  Mostly he just seemed like an entitled jerk to me.

@TMD

If I had a dirty mind— which I emphatically do not, how dare I even suggest such a thing— I might add to those:  29A (badly spelled), as well as 65A, 50A, and 41A.









I'll 11(myself)D

@Jeb Jones 

Probably true, but I think Spanish words have migrated into common English parlance much more often. 

Mexican restaurants: carne asada, enchilada, chili con queso, and so on. Or movies: "Hasta la vista, baby." And let's not forget the NYT crossword's ubiquitous use of  Ole!

@Francis 

As a reptilian, I resent your last paragraph. 🦎

On a more serious note: any sort of critique of a puzzle often gets misconstrued as "complaining" in these comments, which I have always found unfair and often hurtful. There is a difference between somebody bashing a puzzle in a single line of vitriol and another person describing their difficulties in detail - but some people refuse to appreciate it.

@Regine 

I agree with both of your comments (without getting into @B's specific examples).

The comments that bother me are ones like "Do better," or otherwise criticize the creators -- here in a forum where they are speaking only to their peers. That's just someone looking for an audience, because if they actually wanted action on their complaint, they would email the Games staff. (And if, given the benefit of the doubt they did that, it would behoove them to say so. IMHO!)

@Chet 

Most objective and informed comment of the year, easily. Five stars.











[That was sarcasm]

@Mimi 

Why not keep one's options open?

Thursday puzzles can be fun, if you want a bit of a brain-teasing challenge.  Just being aware of that going in can help a lot !

@jp inframan 

Huh? You think ALL the NYT puzzles are getting worse? 

Thursday puzzles are almost invariably enriched by some gimmick or another. That's the challenge, which many of us prize.  This one was as tricky as they come, but the construction was admirable. (Or so it seemed to me.)

@Andrzej 

Well, according to some, our trivia is not just trivia, it's American exceptionalism trivia.

Still, I think, almost by definition, any country's trivia is about equal to any other country's.

